Created attachment 241037 Eclipse log containing Java source and error informatino
I wanted to try out functionality of Java 8 in Eclipse.
However a simple Java file makes the compiler crash with an Internal compiler error. Log file is attached which also contains the Java source forcing the crash.
I'm using Java JDK 1.8.0 and Kepler 4.3.2. I have added Java 8 support as described on https://wiki.eclipse.org/JDT/Eclipse_Java_8_Support_For_Kepler
Thanks for the report - I'll take a look.
Sasi, please take a look. Start by adding a junit test in LambdaExpressionsTest
Created attachment 241313 patch

(In reply to Sasikanth Bharadwaj from comment #3)
Can you say a word on what exactly triggers the AIOOBE? What are the values of n, k and offset you are observing?
Thanks

(In reply to comment #4) > (In reply to Sasikanth Bharadwaj from comment #3) > > Can you say a word on what exactly triggers the AIOOBE? > What are the values of n, k and offset you are observing? > > Thanks The problem is that the potentially applicable method, which is an exact method binding, is actually bound to a method that does not have the same number of parameters as the functional interface method. So, in this case, n = 2, while k = 0. Although the case k = n-1 is handled specially, there is no check to ensure that the number of parameters are same, and it didn't seem right to add the check here, so I added the additional condition to the loop so that the result would be the same as when the potentially applicable method has more parameters than the functional interface method

(In reply to Sasikanth Bharadwaj from comment #5) > The problem is that the potentially applicable method, which is an exact > method binding, is actually bound to a method that does not have the same > number of parameters as the functional interface method. So, in this case, n > = 2, while k = 0. Although the case k = n-1 is handled specially, there is > no check to ensure that the number of parameters are same, and it didn't > seem right to add the check here, so I added the additional condition to the > loop so that the result would be the same as when the potentially applicable > method has more parameters than the functional interface method
Thanks for explaining. Looking into the spec (18.2.1 under "A constraint formula of the form MethodReference T, where T mentions at least one inference variable, is reduced as follows: ") I believe we shouldn't even try to infer this method reference. The key item is:
- "Otherwise, if there does not exist a potentially applicable method for the method reference when targeting T, the constraint reduces to false. "
What is a "potentially applicable method"? For the inexact case, we resolve the method reference against the target type which should find the mismatching arity and return null. For the exact case, however, we simply use the existing exactMethodBinding, which seems to be wrong. Checks for parameter arity and type parameter arity have to be added according to 15.13.1 "Second, ...".
See also that 18.2.1 after elaborating on "n = k+1" continues: "In all other cases, n = k, ...".
For a quick solution, adding s.t. like if (n != k+offset) return FALSE; should yield the correct outcome.
For a more thorough solution we should probably add more checks into ReferenceExpression.findCompileTimeMethodTargeting() (inside if (this.exactMethodBinding != null) { .. }).
Thanks Stephan I will attach a new patch with appropriate checks for parameter arity and type argument arity

Created attachment 241810 New patch with checks for parameter & type argument arity
New patch with checks for parameter & type argument arity

New patch attached with appropriate checks for parameter arity and type argument arity. Also includes new test 430766a for type argument mismatch. Stephan, please take a look
Thanks Sasikanth
Stephan, thanks for reviewing this and help taking this to completion.

Two background remarks on RE.findCompileTimeMethodTargeting(): - The intention is basically to provide API for JLS 15.13.1 - Checking for exactMethodBinding was intended as a short cut if resolution does not depend on the target type, assuming that relevant checks have already been performed at the initial resolveType(..).

(In reply to Stephan Herrmann from comment #12) > Two background remarks on RE.findCompileTimeMethodTargeting():
Thanks Stephan,
> - The intention is basically to provide API for JLS 15.13.1
OK, in that case the snippet proposed in comment#11 should work.
> - Checking for exactMethodBinding was intended as a short cut if resolution > does not depend on the target type, assuming that relevant checks have > already been performed at the initial resolveType(..).
Relevant checks could not have been performed in the absence of a target type which is what puts us here ?

(In reply to Srikanth Sankaran from comment #13) > Relevant checks could not have been performed in the absence of a target type > which is what puts us here ?
I think so, yes.
So the exactMethodBinding _can_ be used as half the solution - this part cannot change with a given target type, but checks and parameterization still have to be applied specifically.

(In reply to Stephan Herrmann from comment #14) > (In reply to Srikanth Sankaran from comment #13)
> > Relevant checks could not have been performed in the absence of a target type > > which is what puts us here ? > > I think so, yes. > > So the exactMethodBinding _can_ be used as half the solution - this part > cannot change with a given target type, but checks and parameterization > still have to be applied specifically.
I think type inference's needs are met by two separate APIs - findCompileTimeMethodTargeting() and isExactMethodReference(). It is not clear to me that findCompileTimeMethodTargeting() needs to do anything beyond what is in comment#11, in particular it should not have to consult/manipulate the field exactMethodBinding at all.
I also suspect that the call to createParameterizedGenericMethod in comment#11's snippet should not be required at all, as this was a band aid to cover for the short coming on the part of the code that computes the exact method reference which should be directly fixed in Scope.getExactMethod and Scope.getExactConstructor

(In reply to Sasikanth Bharadwaj from comment #16)
> For a regular method, the compatibility check is not performed until the > return type is a proper type
Should we be doing the similar thing for array constructor reference also ??
Created attachment 242153 New patch with proposed changes

(In reply to comment #17) > (In reply to Sasikanth Bharadwaj from comment #16) > > > For a regular method, the compatibility check is not performed until the > > return type is a proper type > > Should we be doing the similar thing for array constructor reference also ?? Adding the additional check solves the problem. And the additional call to createParameterizedGenericMethod in comment#11's snippet is not required like you said. Attaching the new patch with the proposed changes and tests. No new failures in AllJava8Tests with these changes.
